{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Cloud*. Using *JIRA Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRASERVER-2345].
  {panel}

Our testers are sometimes mis-entering (or not entering at all) the "Affected Versions" on new bug reports.

It would be useful to be able to (optionally) set a "Current Version" in the version setup of the project administration screens.  Then, when creating new issues, the "Affected Version" would default to whatever the current version is.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Cloud*. Using *JIRA Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRASERVER-2330].
  {panel}

The new project statistics portlet is cool but it would be alot more usefull to me if it had the ability to be filtered by version.  We have a large amount of issues in our jira installation.  Most of those issues are unverified, possibly unscheduled and are generally crud.  I only really care about the scheduled issues that are in the current or the next releease or two out.  So statistics for the whole project get skewed by this amount of old/unscheduled/unverified issues.  

It would be nice to be able to filter a stats portlet by version.  So it basically displays the same way but only calculates stats for a specific version.  Of course, it would be nice to see that version in the portlet header or something.  Also for different ways I configure the portlet (Summary,Components,Assignee) it would be nice to specify whether I want to filter on Affects or Fix version.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Cloud*. Using *JIRA Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRASERVER-2322].
  {panel}

If a user leaves the firm and his account has to be removed, JIRA won't let us delete because there are still unresolved issues reported by that user. JIRA should allow to transfer ownership of these issues to another user and delete this account safely.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Cloud*. Using *JIRA Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRASERVER-2276].
  {panel}

We need to improve the events dispatching system so that it's more Swing like (ie events and listeners are more fine grained - IssueAssignedEvent and AssignIssueListener).

This would allow us much more flexibility in the event dispatching / listening system.

Also we need to ensure the order of listeners, make listeners installed / uninstalled, allow you to install more than one of a given listener and make sure system listeners occur in the right order.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Cloud*. Using *JIRA Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRASERVER-2236].
  {panel}

I'd would like to be able to not allow a user to submit a bug to be fixed for a version thats already released.  These bugs generally fall by the wayside and I have to periodically go move then to the appropriate release.  For example, a user will log a bug against version 4.0.0 when they should have been logging it against 4.0.1.  4.0.0 being the released version and 4.0.1 will be its maintenance release.

I really don't see a reason why anyone would want to log a bug against a released version anyway but I would be happy to be able to have an option for it somewhere.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Cloud*. Using *JIRA Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRASERVER-2221].
  {panel}

I was just reassigning a few issues (to be able to delete a user). A collegue asked if I did the reassigning. It would be nice if the email says who reassigned the issue. It now states 'this issue was reassigned', just add 'by userid'

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Cloud*. Using *JIRA Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRASERVER-2220].
  {panel}

Somebody left our company, so I wanted to delete this user, yet Jira says I can't.

Deleting a user with open or assigned issues should be possible, reassigning all issues to the lead.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Cloud*. Using *JIRA Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRASERVER-2212].
  {panel}

For the 'Project Table' portlet I can choose the number of columns the projects are shown in.

Something similar would be great for the Saved Filters portlet, as the number can sometimes be quite high, and this list gets lengthy!

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Cloud*. Using *JIRA Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRASERVER-2186].
  {panel}

We use Jira for customer support issue tracking. In some cases, quite often, we would like to make some minor changes to the issues, that would not need to be notified at all. 

We would like to have a checkbox in all screens that eventually send to notification: "Send notification" that we could uncheck when we do not want to send a notification. This action should ideally have its own permission so that customers could never suppress notifications from their actions.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Cloud*. Using *JIRA Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRASERVER-2183].
  {panel}

We should be able to search on issues that have been modified by a certain user in any period of time.

We will need to search for changegroups and actions.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Cloud*. Using *JIRA Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRASERVER-2177].
  {panel}

Convert http://forums.atlassian.com/thread.jspa?forumID=46&threadID=3600&messageID=87635031#87635031
to a FAQ entry.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Cloud*. Using *JIRA Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRASERVER-2159].
  {panel}

It would be very handy to send an optional email when adding a comment. Nice if there could be a drop-down box to select a user in the project.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Cloud*. Using *JIRA Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRASERVER-2115].
  {panel}

I want to be able to create a notification scheme based on issue priority, e.g. a scheme that will only notify members of Blocker or Critical issues, rather than all issues by default.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Cloud*. Using *JIRA Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRASERVER-2106].
  {panel}

The concept is similar to email forwarding.  You are looking at an issue and you know that some other person would benefit from knowing about changes to an issue, so you "forward" the issue to them.  The person or persons you are forwarding the issue to would receive an email notification letting them know that you have forwarded the issue to them.  The forward recipient(s) would have the ability to delete the forward if they decided at some point that they were no longer interested.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Cloud*. Using *JIRA Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRASERVER-2088].
  {panel}

I'm trying to use the UserBrowser screen in the Administration options to find the details of a user, and all I have to go on is his name.  I got that from a New Issue email notification, which doesn't contain his email address; I can't just view the issue in question as it was lost in the recent server crash and is no longer there (that's why I'm wanting to email him...)

Unfortunately, the screen only allows for filtering on Email address or Group, so I'm having to page through all 600+ users to find him.  It would have been useful if I could have filtered the list on (a case-insensitive substring match of) the Fullname field as well.  For that matter, I can think of circumstances when filtering on Username might be useful too, so why not add that too and have all the fields available for filtering?

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Cloud*. Using *JIRA Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRASERVER-2067].
  {panel}

JIRA sends out a lot of emails. This is fine. But the emails that are sendt out to the current user when the same user does changes only fills up the mailbox.

Each user can turn off this option, but it would be nice if administrator could do this for all users.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Cloud*. Using *JIRA Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRASERVER-2060].
  {panel}

We need a way to give our customers ability to browse a project, but limited only to the issues they have created.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Cloud*. Using *JIRA Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRASERVER-2026].
  {panel}

I think it would be useful if, when there is no filter selected, either manually, or stored in the session, and a user clicks on the 'Find Issues' link, if the page would display the same contents as clicking the 'Filter: All' link.

I know that I've clicked on 'find issues' many times, only to have my filter selection cleared, and then either have to click on 'Filter: All', or the 'Filters' quick link to select a filter.  It would be a time saver it the list filters showed up by default if there was no filter selected.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Cloud*. Using *JIRA Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRASERVER-2020].
  {panel}

a generic time tracking report seems like a good option. Instead of only having the possibility to generate a time tracking report for one project at a time only, it might be handy to generate a list with the “time bars” as can be seen on top of one project’s time tracking report. This list can be custom generated, eg. One can choose to have a list of all projects, one or more project groups and /or one or more projects. The existing time tracking report may continue to exist, of course. 

A “report” button on the JIRA portal would be nice though. We consider the current place where one can generate a time tracking report quite clumsy to use.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Cloud*. Using *JIRA Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRASERVER-2015].
  {panel}

While issues assigned to me is useful, the personal roadmap feature is even more critical so you can quickly identify the specific issues for the current version you are working on.  Allow configuring it as a portlet so it shows on the home page.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Cloud*. Using *JIRA Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRASERVER-2012].
  {panel}

The size of the issue navigator form is getting unwieldy. 

We should reduce the size of the form by moving it into a series of tabs. The initial thoughts for tabs are Project, Constants, Dates, Users and Custom Fields.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Cloud*. Using *JIRA Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRASERVER-1984].
  {panel}

All current notifications are related to operations on issue.

Some project related events might be interesting to be notified of. The most obvious I see is 'Version Released' but other could be interesting such as version archived, component added, component removed, ...

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Cloud*. Using *JIRA Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRASERVER-1981].
  {panel}

Whilst the addition of new functionality to allow multiple permissions to be added to a group in one transaction is very useful, it would be even better if 1 or more permission can be added to multiple groups in one hit. 

I spotted this when I was trying to add the new permissions of "Schedule Issues" and "Move issues" to existing groups, and at present I have to do each group (of which we have many!) in turn.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Cloud*. Using *JIRA Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRASERVER-1971].
  {panel}

Would like to be able to change a resolution before closing an issue.

e.g. we have a resolution of "Awaiting Validation" and it would be nice, if the validation is successful, to change this to Fixed before we close the issue.

Ideally we would like to be able to add statuses - I will raise this in a separate issue following this one.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Cloud*. Using *JIRA Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRASERVER-1946].
  {panel}

an automated work log feature would be great. If I start work on an issue, I'd click start and JIRA stops recording time for the previos issue (if any) and starts time trackking for the new one. I should be able to add a comment to the first / final / any time record and maybe adjust recorded times (in case I simply forgot to stop recoding before going home!) Since we are still a small team, we do have many interruptions and issue switches during a day.

-- Kai Bounin

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Cloud*. Using *JIRA Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRASERVER-1940].
  {panel}

In the administration part of JIRA it is possible to enable/disable the ability to create unassigned issues. This is now done globally and therefore affects all projects, but it should be possible to do this on a project level.

This could be extended further so it actually resembles the global permissions vs. the project specific permissions, so that every global option also could be decided on a project level (Allow users to vote on issues, Allow users to watch issues, Allow Attachments, Allow unassigned issues, etc).

-- Thomas Watson

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Cloud*. Using *JIRA Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRASERVER-1917].
  {panel}

We need to implement concurrency controls for update functions.

-- Edwin

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Cloud*. Using *JIRA Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRASERVER-1895].
  {panel}

The ability to use the Alt-H, Alt-B etc... key shortcuts on the web interface to jump to different parts of the application is a great feature.  I'd like to see these type of shortcuts expanded to more options on each interface.  I.e., instead of just the main navigation options having shortcut key bindings, add them to most links on each interface.  Being able to navigate a web interface without using the mouse would be incredible.

-- Ryan Daigle

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Cloud*. Using *JIRA Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRASERVER-1866].
  {panel}

It would be nice if the automated backup/export service also could backup all the attachments (this should ofcause be up to the user if he wants to).

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Cloud*. Using *JIRA Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRASERVER-1857].
  {panel}

The time tracking funtionality of Jira would be much more useful for our  Project management if there was a high level summary of the remaining work available.

One way that is probably easy to implement would be to print a sum of the remaing work for each version in the roadmap, alongside the version status bar: "(38 of 42 issues are unresolved, 86 days of work remaining)"

Such a report would be a great help for scheduling release dates. Together with the release date per version feature mentioned in JRA-1012, this would really be fantastic, as it would allow us to continuously track whether our schedule is still realistic by just looking at the roadmap.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Cloud*. Using *JIRA Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRASERVER-1849].
  {panel}

We need an icon for the issue picker (currently only linked from the linkIssue page).  

At the same time we should consolidate all icons for popups.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Cloud*. Using *JIRA Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRASERVER-1817].
  {panel}

For releases, I want to call filters from an external script (in this case: apache ant). When in private mode, this gives you an information page about filters.

URL: http://myserver/jira/secure/IssueNavigator.jspa?requestId=10031&decorator=printable&tempMax=1000

I like the option to call a page, optionally referencing a named filter, specifying the user & password as arguments, outputting a nice HTML page containing 'resolved issues' and 'known issues' for a certain release.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Cloud*. Using *JIRA Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRASERVER-1814].
  {panel}

After you stop working on an issue, automatically forward to 'log work done'.

This seems logical and forces users to summarize their work done.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Cloud*. Using *JIRA Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRASERVER-1799].
  {panel}

Listeners are a bit 'smelly' at the moment. They should be configurable objects like services.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Cloud*. Using *JIRA Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRASERVER-1781].
  {panel}

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Cloud*. Using *JIRA Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRASERVER-1771].
  {panel}

I have defined a few filters which show up in my 'dashboard'. However it would be nice if it would show the number (count) of objects found by the filters.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Cloud*. Using *JIRA Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRASERVER-1759].
  {panel}

A great function could be the possibility, at project administration level, to define the Workflow between issues, for example the PM can define a chained flow of different issues! example : Issue types ( requirement ), ( development ), ( Test ), ( implementation ), ( documentation ), ( Q&A ). with Parallel routing flow. The PM assigne the detailed business requirement specificatoin to a process manager, when it's resolved it goes to a predefined deveopment team ( Multiple assignement ), when it's solved automatically goes in 3 parallel phases ( test & implementation & documentation ) when all 3 issues are solved it goes to the Q & A.  We have done it at this moment trough a listener, added a java class and manipulating everytime manually a file property. An idea could be manage the file property with an XML file, create this file trough a xml workflow designer ( like reactor studio )and let it read by Jira.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Cloud*. Using *JIRA Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRASERVER-1727].
  {panel}

With a large number of projects, and lots of users, some of our project managers tend to get innuendated with e-mails. We have the project manager get notified for assigns, edits, resolved, closes, etc. Everything basically. They want to have all these notifications, because they need to know when status changes, but they don't want all of the e-mails.

What about a way to batch the changes, PRIOR to batching the sending of the e-mails.  For example, say an issue is edited (component and fix for version set), then assigned to a developer with a comment, and then the developer adds another comment, all in under one minute.  This would result in three e-mails, all sent out one minute from now.  Why not batch the changes, and every minute poll the "notification batch", generate ONE e-mail that lists the changes made to the issue.  This would significantly reduce e-mails, while still giving a project manager/lead the ability to keep up to speed on the issue.  Just a thought.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Cloud*. Using *JIRA Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRASERVER-1720].
  {panel}

It would be nice if there was a quick way to determine what the current version of a project is.

One thing we've been doing manually is on the Project Title we put the current version in () i.e. (v.2.2.60).

This is a pain though, as we have several projects listed.  I know that projects may not have versions but if they do they could pull the last released version and stick it in the Project Title.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Cloud*. Using *JIRA Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRASERVER-1714].
  {panel}

When you make changes to the description of an issue, the entire before/after description is displayed, which is potentially a lot to look at. Some of our issues have non-trivial descriptions associated with them. It would be nice to be able to display only the diff of the descriptions... someone has written a diff class that is pretty easy to use:

http://www.bmsi.com/java/

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Cloud*. Using *JIRA Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRASERVER-1713].
  {panel}

The ability to categorize our time for logging work would be very beneficial.  Currently we have added a custom field to the task for bill as, but this doesn't allow multiple people working an issue to bill that time worked differently.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Cloud*. Using *JIRA Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRASERVER-1688].
  {panel}

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Cloud*. Using *JIRA Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRASERVER-1676].
  {panel}

It would be helpful for a supervisor or administrator to be able to log work for someone else.  Right now, you can only log work for yourself.

This should probably be configured as a separate permission, so that only certain people could log work for others.

This is related to JRA-1669.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Cloud*. Using *JIRA Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRASERVER-1649].
  {panel}

Sometimes I need to close JIRA down due to maintenance.

Right now I do this by only allowing JIRA administrators to login. This has the bad side effect that anybody else are told that "Sorry, your username and password are incorrect - please try again.". Then they try to require a new password (and do this about 3 times before they contact me).

If they instead got the message "Sorry, you are not able to login at the moment due to system maintenance" it would be much better.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Cloud*. Using *JIRA Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRASERVER-1638].
  {panel}

we'd really like the capability to create pseudo-columns in search results based on aggregate (i.e. "group by") functions. in particular, count/min/max/sum (std deviation would be cool too but not quite as necessary).  obviously count would work on any field grouped by, min/max would work on dates and numerics, sum would work on numerics only.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Cloud*. Using *JIRA Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRASERVER-1622].
  {panel}

It would be nice to have the ability to Export the Change Log or in that case any amount of data to XML.  I realize there is the ability to view the data in XML, but I cannot hook into this if the Project does not have "Anyone" under Browse Project and the project I want this information for is not set that way.  I tried saving the XML that was in the browser but it was just a blank file.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Cloud*. Using *JIRA Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRASERVER-1613].
  {panel}

When we create an issue we also create an internal bug test case with the same issue name. So, many times, we'll have an issue description like:

"Blah blah blah doesn't work. See SMA-102.cs and SMA-102.xml for bug reproduction."

JIRA seems to automatically hotlink the SMA-102 to the actual issue inside JIRA. This is really cool, actually, but it would be nice if it were smart enough to look for more text and not link if it existed. So, putting SMA-102 by itself, surrounded by spaces, would be cause a hot link, but putting SMA-102anythingelsehere would not.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Cloud*. Using *JIRA Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRASERVER-1585].
  {panel}

Supporting wiki style writing in description and comments fields would allow to put some formatting easily.

This feature is inspired of this very neat simple tool (http://www.jhorman.org/wikidoclet) that allows to use wiki style syntax in javadoc comments.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Cloud*. Using *JIRA Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRASERVER-1566].
  {panel}

We would like to be able to assign multiple notification schemas to a Project. 

We have global notifications that are the same for each project. We would also like addtional notifications to be sent based ona the individual project. Currently we need to duplicate the same settings in new notification schemas for each project.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Cloud*. Using *JIRA Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRASERVER-1563].
  {panel}

In most cases it is enough to see the comment in the filter management view. Would it be possible to have it enabled/disabled from the dashboard ?

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Cloud*. Using *JIRA Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRASERVER-1549].
  {panel}

{panel:title=Atlassian Status as of 22 May 2013|borderStyle=solid|borderColor=#3C78B5| titleBGColor=#3C78B5| bgColor=#E7F4FA}
Hi everyone,

Thanks so much for your votes and comments on this issue.

JIRA 6.0 has been released with the ability to edit usernames and we all hope you take it for a spin! JIRA 6.0 contains lots of other goodness and you can read the full release notes [here|https://confluence.atlassian.com/display/JIRA/JIRA+6.0+Release+Notes].

Cheers,

Roy
JIRA Product Management
roy at atlassian dot com

{panel}

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Cloud*. Using *JIRA Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRASERVER-1542].
  {panel}

We can add custom fields to an issue. Would liek to be able to ad custom field to a comment. This would allow a catagory type drop down when adding a comment.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Cloud*. Using *JIRA Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRASERVER-1535].
  {panel}

We should allow a PDF version of each issue, so that issues can be sent electronically, or printed in a nicer format.

